article.description:
Michael Jordan said goodbye to the All-Star game with his eyes teary and
his game a bit blemished as the West beat the East 155-145 in
double overtime Sunday night.

article.headline: West gets the win, but the day belonged to MJ

article.linkText: West gets the win, but the day belonged to MJ
article.story:
ATLANTA -- All along, the story was about Michael Jordan -- how he'd be honored in his last All-Star Game and whether he'd leave the court in style. The fans who packed Philips Arena for the MJ lovefest got their Hollywood ending in overtime when Jordan's fallaway jumper appeared to give the East a 138-136 win over the West and add one more highlight to his legacy. But from that point on, the NBA's 52nd All-Star Game didn't follow the script. The ad-libs, in chronological order, included a controversial foul by Jermaine O'Neal, two game-tying free throws by Kobe Bryant to force a second overtime and a dominating performance by Kevin Garnett in the extra five minutes in a 155-145 victory by the West on Sunday night. Garnett scored nine of his game-high 37 points in the second overtime to earn Most Valuable Player honors, as the action featured more drama than usual for an All-Star Game. Both sides were willing to do whatever was required to win the game, even if it meant playing defense. "It got really, really intense," said Garnett, who played 41 of the 58 minutes. "I think the second overtime was really, really intense. I think guys started to pick up their play."
All-Time All-Star Scoring
Player Points
1. Michael Jordan 262
2. Kareem Abdul-Jabbar 251
3. Oscar Robertson 246
4. Bob Pettit 224
5. Julius Erving 221
6. Elgin Baylor 218
7. Wilt Chamberlain 191
8. Isiah Thomas 185
9. John Havlicek 179
10. Magic Johnson 176
O'Neal got a little too active on defense after Jordan, from the right baseline, sank his improbable rainbow jumper over Shawn Marion to break a 136-136 tie. Jason Kidd deflected the ensuing inbounds pass, but Bryant chased the loose ball into the right corner. O'Neal ran into Bryant just as he was about to heave a desperation 3-pointer with one second left. "The foul the ref called was unbelievable," O'Neal said. "Even Kobe said it wasn't a foul." Bryant pleaded innocent, too, of ruining Jordan's party. "I was put in a tough spot -- I was just trying to put up a shot," he said. Bryant could've won the game, but made only the first and third free throws to bring about five more minutes of basketball. With Jordan on the bench – after logging 36 minutes in his 20-point performance – the West followed Garnett's lead as the Timberwolves forward scored six straight points for a 145-138 lead. Paul Pierce's dunk cut the East's deficit to 145-140, but consecutive 3-pointers by Steve Francis and Bryant pushed the West out to a 151-140 cushion with 2:44 remaining. "It was a fun ending any way you look at it," Jordan said. "It was a competitive game. Obviously, I would've liked to have won the game with me making the (winning) shot or my teammates making the shot. (But) it didn't happen that way." Jordan, who thanked the fans during an emotional halftime ceremony honoring him, had the opportunity to be the hero at the end of regulation. He went one-on-one with Marion, but his fadeaway jumper rolled off the front rim to keep the game tied at 120. Marion actually played better defense the second time West head coach Rick Adelman enlisted him to be the Jordan stopper at the end of the first OT. Jordan, though, provided the moment the sellout crowd of 20,325 had been waiting for. "It was a great shot. It was a great moment," said East head coach Isiah Thomas, who happens to be just a tad familiar with Jordan's heroics from their Bulls-Pistons playoff battles. "The fans went crazy. It was nice … very nice." "I didn't think it was going in," Marion said. "But it went in." "He made that last shot, but we got a chance to tie it up," West guard Gary Payton said of Jordan. "It would've been nice if he would've won the MVP award … but we won."
